          "body": "The chapter does not end with qualifications. It ends with Christ. Verse 16 — almost certainly an early Christian hymn or confessional fragment — narrates the saving arc in six aorist verbs: *revealed in the flesh, vindicated in the Spirit, seen by angels, proclaimed among the nations, believed on in the world, taken up in glory*. The structure is likely chiastic (flesh/Spirit, angels/nations, world/glory) or three couplets (earthly manifestation, cosmic witness, universal proclamation). Paul cites it because the *mystery of godliness* is not abstract piety — it is the incarnate, vindicated, ascended Christ. Every qualification in this chapter is grounded here. Overseers and deacons do not embody civic virtue; they embody the cruciform pattern of the Lord whose flesh was real, whose vindication was the resurrection, and whose glory now governs the household they serve."
